metadata.name: Time Scale #32
metadata.description:
Dear f_x_h_a_s_h

Sorry for the delay in replying. My apologies.

I thought time was absolute.
But what is really absolute is the speed of light.
We are bound by time, but this is a collective illusion.
It is a convenient collective illusion.
Time for images is frames.
Our perception of time changes with the computation time for each frame.
But for Art, it is the same time.
Time is relative.

Now, is this reply belated?
May I withdraw my initial apology?

uesən

metadata.name: hashGame #56
metadata.description:
Conway's life game suggests many things.
Something that keeps solidifying all the time
Things that keep moving
That which disappears
What is born
The rules are simple, but they are based on a perfect balance.
Phenomena that happen before your eyes can be seen forever.

Unique hashes move by the rules of the game of life.
Long-lived things become brighter and brighter.
Tunnels that move in all directions and explosions that spread out from the center force complex rules onto pixels.
Our activities are also pixels somewhere.

metadata.name: FairyCells II #260
metadata.description:
FairyCells II is intended as a logical continuation of the first FairyCells series. By dropping the plotter drawing constraint, new perspectives for exploration appeared.
This is how these cells began to intertwine, live together, mutate and change color, like an evolving system.

What surprises me the most in this new series, is the stories appearing behind each new composition. See how these abstracts shapes can come to life and narrate us things through our imagination.

Each color palette takes us into a different world, drawing a very specific atmosphere.

As me, let yourself be carried away by these stories 💫 !

Artwork by Julien_Espagnon, 2022.

Control : Press « S » to save the image as a PNG.

metadata.name: LAISSEZ FAIRE #24
metadata.description:
In creating this piece, I found myself drawn to the intersection where technology meets literature, a space where code and creativity become inseparable. It's a unique blend of Aldous Huxley's "Brave New World" and the unpredictable nature of AI-generated visuals.

Huxley's dystopian vision always struck a chord with me, especially in today's rapidly advancing technological landscape. I saw parallels between his world and the way generative art evolves - both shaped by their environments, reflecting fears, hopes, and the inherent chaos of their times.

But what really fascinated me was how human touch still played a role. Much like the characters in "Brave New World" wrestling with destiny, the AI visuals in my work, though algorithmically birthed, were guided by my hand. They're not just a reflection of the text but a response to it, engaging in a dialogue that goes beyond mere replication.

This isn't just a generative token; it's a question, a conversation. It's my way of exploring where we stand at this crossroads of art, literature, and technology. In crafting this piece, I found myself wondering, what does our Brave New World look like? How do we balance the precision of code with the fluidity of human emotion? And in a world increasingly dictated by algorithms, where do we fit in?

I invite you to join me in this exploration. Let's unravel the tapestry, decode the symbols, and discover what it means to be human in a world where art and AI coalesce.

- Press "T" to save the text contained within the composition, derived from it´s specific chapter 
- Press "S" to save a .png of the composition

metadata.name: Solace #238
metadata.description:
Solace is an algorithm that generates artworks of sand dunes. It draws hundreds of thousands of tiny points according to a probability distribution calculated from the positions of the dunes.

The logic to divide the dunes into light and dark sides is simple, but produces some interesting chaotic behaviour. These are details that weren't hard-coded but emerge organically, such as the patterns on the spines of the dunes or the stripes around their bases.

Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run, especially when the number of dunes is high.

Created by lunarean.

metadata.name: Primitifs systématiques #94
metadata.description:
Primitifs systématiques is the first generative instalment of David Umemoto’s studies of space and volume. Placed at the crux of brutalism and minimalism, these structures based on the original stackable concrete piece Primitif 04 evoke impossible paths yet to be explored. 

The original Primitif 04 has been both preserved and dented, conserved and enhanced. It is still here. But it cannot be found, only encountered. Throughout your explorations of the Primitifs systématiques, you will find that its original shapes have been multiplied, rotated, re-ordered to create new structures. After spending some time exploring its paths, when you stop looking for it, you will realize that 04 is still here, intact.

Lines of work chosen for this piece also draw a perspective. The orientation of the primitives pulls directly towards an intense source of light. Sometimes it is visible, sometimes it is not. This perfect alignment is a call to life. They who look at the sunrise with relief cannot be anything but hopeful. But how can we project life on a concrete behemoth? Stand long enough in front of it, and you too will see that we have no choice but to.

----

Primitifs systématiques is the generative art genesis piece of David Umemoto. It was built in collaboration with Anaglyphic. It is the first collaborative spatial token made available on the anaver.se.

metadata.name: Mur #310
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Pachinko #32
metadata.description:
A playful and colorful pixel lottery running wild in your Browser !
Interactive, generative ( outputs may slightly vary ... ) 
- press 'p' anytime to pause
- press 'c' to clear and redraw
- press any number from '1' to '6' to change the numbers of slices 
- press 'm' a few times and ... you'll see

Made with few code skills but love, Maths and Trials !

metadata.name: gate bridge #28
metadata.description:
We very often connect different events, pictures and all the chaos in our head. We create bridges between incompatible things. We have learned how to create a connection between numbers, 0 and 1 and create a completely new art.

This artwork creates bridges out of chaos. The lines intersect creating a sea of different and independent patterns. Did I say independent? No. Between them there are bridges of the same patterns.

metadata.name: Annihilate This Week #22
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to "Saturday Night's Alright (For Fighting)" (project #14045). Same algorithm of the previous one, only slightly modified, the main difference is that here the daily variations are all mixed up together and the output doesn't change based on the current day.

This is intended to be a gift for all collectors and the community of fx(hash) that showed so much support for the "Saturday" project, really beyond my expectations.

50% of the royalties goes to the minter, do with the piece whatever you'd like, hold it, sell or trade it, or even burn it if you really don't like it :)

Thank you!

----

Made with p5.js
